For example:
```
const result = [1, 2].reduce(
    (partialResult, actualValue) =&gt; Object.assign({}, partialResult, {[someKey]: someValue]}), {});
```

Either modify the code so that you&#39;re not mutating the object, which means you&#39;ll have to copy it each time:

```
const result = [1, 2].reduce((partialResult, actualValue) =&gt; {
    return {
      ...partialResult,
      [someKey]: someValue,
    }
}, {});
```

Or disable the lint rule (either for this specific line if you like the lint rule in general, or globally if you think it&#39;s an unnecessary restriction)

You can use [`map`][1] and [`Object.fromEntries`][2] to create the object all-at-once (as far as your code is concerned) rather than mutating or copying the object:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const someKey = &quot;foo&quot;;
    const result = Object.fromEntries(
      [1, 2].map(value =&gt; [someKey + value, value])
    //                     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^---- see my comment on the question and
    //                                         note below
    );
    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

`fromEntries` creates an object from an array of entries, where each entry is a `[key, value]` array.

Note that I&#39;ve used `someKey + value` as the key because you haven&#39;t said how you get the key, and I assume you&#39;re not just using the **same** key every time, since as I commented [here][3], if you were you&#39;d be replacing the property value every time if you did and end up with an object with a single property, making the entire loop pointless.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/fromEntries
  [3]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58203723/tslint-no-object-mutation-while-building-object-with-reduce/58203842#comment102785971_58203723

